clinical_study.brief_title: Phase 2 Study of ISIS 681257 (AKCEA-APO(a)-LRx) in Participants With Hyperlipoproteinemia(a) and Cardiovascular Disease
clinical_study.official_title: A Randomized, Double-blind, Placebo-Controlled, Dose-Ranging Phase 2 Study of ISIS 681257 (AKCEA-APO(a)-LRx) Administered Subcutaneously to Patients With Hyperlipoproteinemia(a) and Established Cardiovascular Disease (CVD)

brief_summary.textblock: This is a multicenter, randomized, double-blind, placebo-controlled, dose-ranging study to evaluate the safety, including tolerability, of ISIS 681257 and to assess the efficacy of different doses and dosing regimens of ISIS 681257 for reduction of plasma Lipoprotein(a) [Lp(a)] levels in participants with hyperlipoproteinemia(a) and established cardiovascular disease (CVD).

primary_outcome.measure: Percent Change From Baseline in Fasting Lipoprotein A [Lp(a)] at the Primary Analysis Time Point
primary_outcome.time_frame: Baseline and Month 6 (Week 25 for Cohorts A, B and C and Week 27 for Cohorts D and E)
primary_outcome.description: An ANCOVA model was performed on the log ratio of Lp(a) value at the Primary Analysis Time Point to Lp(a) value at Baseline. The estimate of the log ratio was converted back to the original scale and percent change was calculated using formula: = (ratio of Lp(a) value at the Primary Analysis Time Point to Lp(a) value at Baseline - 1) × 100.

primary_outcome.measure: Number of Participants With Treatment Emergent Adverse Events (TEAEs)
primary_outcome.time_frame: Up to 16 weeks post treatment period (up to approximately 1.3 years)
primary_outcome.description: An adverse event (AE) was defined as any unfavorable and unintended sign (including a clinically significant abnormal laboratory finding), symptom, or disease temporally associated with the study or use of investigational drug product, whether or not the AE was considered related to the investigational drug product. TEAEs was defined as any AE with onset after the first administration of study medication through the end of the study, or any event that was present at baseline but worsened in intensity or was subsequently considered drug-related by the Investigator through the end of the study.

primary_outcome.measure: Number of Participants With TEAEs by Maximum Severity
primary_outcome.time_frame: Up to 16 weeks post treatment period (up to approximately 1.3 years)
primary_outcome.description: An AE was defined as any unfavorable and unintended sign (including a clinically significant abnormal laboratory finding), symptom, or disease temporally associated with the study or use of investigational drug product, whether or not the AE was considered related to the investigational drug product. TEAEs was defined as any AE with onset after the first administration of study medication through the end of the study, or any event that was present at baseline but worsened in intensity or was subsequently considered drug-related by the Investigator through the end of the study. The severity of TEAEs was assessed based on the National Cancer Institute's (NCI) Common Terminology Criteria for Adverse Events (CTCAE) version 4.03. TEAEs were graded on a 5-point scale where 1 = Mild, 2 = Moderate, 3 = Severe, 4 = Potentially life-threatening and 5 = Death.

secondary_outcome.time_frame: Baseline and Month 6 (Week 25 for Cohorts A, B and C and Week 27 for Cohorts D and E)
secondary_outcome.description: An ANCOVA model was performed on the log ratio of LDL-C value at the Primary Analysis Time Point to LDL-C value at Baseline. secondary_outcome.measure: Percentage of Participants Who Achieved Plasma Lp(a) ≤ 125 Nanomoles Per Liter (Nmol/L) or ≤ 50 Milligrams Per Deciliter (mg/dL)
secondary_outcome.time_frame: Baseline and Month 6 (Week 25 for Cohorts A, B and C and Week 27 for Cohorts D and E)
secondary_outcome.description: The percentage of participants who achieved ≤ 125 nmol/L or ≤ 50 mg/dL in fasting Lp(a) at the primary analysis time point were compared between each ISIS 681257 treatment group and pooled placebo group using a logistic regression model with log-transformed baseline Lp(a) as a covariate.

arm_group.description: Cohort A participants received 20 milligrams (mg) ISIS 681257, subcutaneous (SC) injection, once every 4 weeks (Q4W), for up to 49 weeks and a maximum of 13 doses.
Cohort B participants received 40 mg of ISIS 681257, SC injection, once Q4W, for up to 49 weeks and a maximum of 13 doses.
Cohort C participants received 60 mg of ISIS 681257, SC injection, once Q4W, for up to 49 weeks and a maximum of 13 doses.
Cohort D participants received 20 mg of ISIS 681257, SC injection, once every 2 weeks (Q2W), for up to 51 weeks and a maximum of 26 doses.
Cohort E participants received 20 mg of ISIS 681257, SC injection, once weekly (QW), for up to 52 weeks and a maximum of 52 doses.
Participants in each cohort were randomized to receive placebo at a dose-matched volume of study drug (ISIS 681257).

criteria.textblock:
Key Inclusion Criteria:
- Clinical diagnosis of CVD defined as documented coronary artery disease, stroke, or peripheral artery disease
- Lp(a) plasma level ≥ 60 mg/dL
- Must be on standard-of-care preventative therapy for other than elevated Lp(a) CVD risk factors
Key Exclusion Criteria:
- Within 6 months of Screening: acute coronary syndrome, major cardiac surgery, or stroke/TIA
- Within 3 months of Screening: coronary, carotid, or peripheral arterial revascularization, major non-cardiac surgery, or lipoprotein apheresis
- Heart failure New York Heart Association (NYHA) class IV

participant_flow.recruitment_details: Participants with a clinical diagnosis of hyperlipoproteinemia(a) and established CVD were enrolled in 31 study centers in United States, Canada, Denmark, Germany and Netherlands between 7th March 2017 to 13th November 2018.
participant_flow.pre_assignment_details: 286 participants were randomized in a 1:1:1:1:1 ratio to Cohorts A, B, C, D or E. In each cohort, participants were randomized in a 5:1 ratio to receive ISIS 681257 or placebo.

measure.population: FAS included all participants who were randomized and received at least 1 dose of study drug (ISIS 681257 or placebo). FAS represented the practically feasible ITT population as delineated in ICH Guideline E9.

outcome.title: Percent Change From Baseline in the Plasma Levels of Apolipoprotein B (apoB)
outcome.description: An ANCOVA model was performed on the log ratio of apoB value at the Primary Analysis Time Point to apoB value at Baseline. The estimate of the log ratio was converted back to the original scale and percent change was calculated using formula: = (ratio of apoB value at the Primary Analysis Time Point to apoB value at Baseline - 1) × 100.
